          <p class='first-para'>
            I thank the Minister for his reply. I shall read carefully what he said. I think that there is a difference between the spirit of his reply&#x2014;and that of course that was an important objective and so on&#x2014;and the actual wording of my amendment which wanted to ensure that having regard to sustainability was part of the principal objective. Perhaps he can explain whether the duty laid on Ofwat is greater than we propose to lay on Ofgem. If there is a difference, why does the DTI think that difference is necessary?
          </p>
        </blockquote>
      </div>
      
      <div class='hentry member_contribution' id='S5LV0656P0-04422'>
        <a name='S5LV0656P0_20040204_GCR_252'>  </a>
        <blockquote cite='http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/people/mr-bryan-davies' class='contribution_text entry-content'>
          <a class='speech-permalink permalink' href='#S5LV0656P0_20040204_GCR_252' title='Link to this speech by Mr Bryan Davies' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
          <cite class='member author entry-title'><a href="/people/mr-bryan-davies" title="Mr Bryan Davies">Lord Davies of Oldham</a></cite>
          <p class='first-para'>
            Ofwat is a different structure from Ofgem. Ofwat has clear environmental and sustainable factors built into its remit and its role. The broad objectives fit into the overall pattern of the principles which affect a range of these utilities.
          </p>
        </blockquote>
      </div>
      
      <div class='hentry member_contribution' id='S5LV0656P0-04423'>
        <a name='S5LV0656P0_20040204_GCR_253'>  </a>
        <blockquote cite='http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/people/ms-susan-miller' class='contribution_text entry-content'>
          <a class='speech-permalink permalink' href='#S5LV0656P0_20040204_GCR_253' title='Link to this speech by Ms Susan Miller' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
